Although the detection of pancreatic carcinoma has been considerably improved by recently developed imaging procedures, differential diagnosis between cancer and benign tumor masses, as well as lymph node staging, is still difficult. In vivo evaluation of regional glucose metabolism by means of positron emission tomography (PET) and fluorine-18-labelled fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) is a new approach utilizing metabolic instead of morphological tumor properties for diagnosis.  
